'''Bruns nystagmus''' is an unusual type of bilateral [[nystagmus]] most commonly occurring in patients with [[Cerebellopontine angle syndrome|cerebellopontine angle tumours]]. It is caused by the combination of slow, large amplitude nystagmus (gaze paretic nystagmus) when looking towards the side of the lesion, and rapid, small amplitude nystagmus (vestibular nystagmus) when looking away from the side of the lesion.<ref name="dejong">{{cite book |title= |last=Campbell |first=William Wesley |coauthors=Russell N. DeJong, Armin F. Haerer |year=2005 |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |isbn=978-0-7817-2767-9 |pages=294}}</ref> It occurs in 11% of patients with [[vestibular schwannoma]], and occurs mainly in patients with larger tumours (67% of patients with tumours over 3.5cm diameter). Bruns nystagmus is also associated with an increased incidence of balance disturbance in patients with vestibular schwannoma.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lloyd SK, Baguley DM, Butler K, Donnelly N, Moffat DA |title=Bruns' nystagmus in patients with vestibular schwannoma |journal=Otol. Neurotol. |volume=30 |issue=5 |pages=625–8 |year=2009 |month=August |pmid=19471169 |doi=10.1097/MAO.0b013e3181a32bec |url=http://meta.wkhealth.com/pt/pt-core/template-journal/lwwgateway/media/landingpage.htm?issn=1531-7129&volume=30&issue=5&spage=625 |accessdate=2011-01-10}}</ref> It may be caused by the compression of both [[Flocculus (cerebellar)|flocculi]], the [[Vestibular system|vestibular]] part of the [[cerebellum]], and improvement in both the nystagmus and balance problems occur commonly after removal of the tumour.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Nedzelski JM |title=Cerebellopontine angle tumors: bilateral flocculus compression as cause of associated oculomotor abnormalities |journal=Laryngoscope |volume=93 |issue=10 |pages=1251–60 |year=1983 |month=October |pmid=6604857 |doi= |url= |accessdate=2011-01-10}}</ref>

Bruns nystagmus is named for [[Ludwig Bruns]] (1858 &ndash; 1915).
